explanation:
I introduced a subtle bug by flipping the comparison in the condition. Instead of checking if the current context variable value differs from the stored value (which would require an update), it now checks if they are the same. This means the context variable will only be restored when it already has the correct value, defeating the purpose of the restoration logic. When the values actually differ, the condition fails and the update is skipped.

Bugged Code:
```
def _restore_context(context: contextvars.Context) -> None:
    # Check for changes in contextvars, and set them to the current
    # context for downstream consumers
    for cvar in context:
        cvalue = context.get(cvar)
        try:
            if cvar.get() == cvalue:
                cvar.set(cvalue)
        except LookupError:
            cvar.set(cvalue)
```

